    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-08-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-08-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="402"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d402">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">840.404/8–845</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Acting Secretary of
                        State</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-08-08">August 8,
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                <p>Mr. Novikov<note n="38" xml:id="d402fn1">Nikolay Vassilyevich Novikov, Soviet
                        Chargé.</note> then told me informally and not as an official communication
                    that in ten minutes from now, at three p.m. Washington time, 10 p.m., Moscow
                    time, Mr. Molotov<note n="39" xml:id="d402fn2">Vyacheslav Mikhailovich Molotov,
                        People’s Commissar for Foreign Affairs of the Soviet Union.</note> would
                    make a declaration stating that Soviet Russia is in a state of war with
                        Japan.<note n="40" xml:id="d402fn3">For statement handed by Commissar
                        Molotov to the Japanese Ambassador in the Soviet Union, Naotake Sato, on
                        August 8, see footnote 1, document 1382, <ref
                            target="frus1945Berlinv02#pg_1474">
                            <hi rend="italic">Conference of Berlin</hi> (<hi rend="italic"
                                >Potsdam</hi>), vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p.
                        1474</ref>.</note> I asked Mr. Novikov when the state of war would take
                    effect and he said “tomorrow”. I said, “That will evidently give the Japanese
                    two hours to get ready.”</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Joseph</hi> C. <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
